# Spring Boot Ultimate Production Rules - API Design (10 Rules)

1. Use resource-oriented URLs with nouns, not verbs.
2. Follow HTTP semantics strictly for `GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, and `DELETE`.
3. Version APIs explicitly (for example `/api/v1/...`) and maintain deprecation windows.
4. Return consistent response envelopes for success and failure across all services.
5. Use proper status codes (`200/201/204/400/401/403/404/409/422/500/503`) with stable meaning.
6. Validate all request payloads at boundary with Bean Validation and reject invalid input early.
7. Support pagination, sorting, and filtering for list endpoints by default.
8. Keep API contracts stable; additive changes are preferred over breaking schema changes.
9. Publish machine-readable API contracts (OpenAPI) and keep them synchronized with implementation.
10. Enforce idempotency for retry-prone operations (payment, order submission, callbacks).
